Ahead of the 2019 presidential Inauguration, the Federal Government has reeled out several activities lined up to mark May 29 and June 12 as Nigeria’s first Democracy Day.  Minister of Information and Culture, Lai Mohamed, who spoke at a World Press Conference in Abuja, stated that President Muhammadu Buhari and his Vice Professor, Yemi Osinbajo will on May 29, be officially sworn in for a second term in office and other major activities of the inauguration will be shifted to June 12.  While reeling out the activities of the celebration the minister noted that the inauguration officially kicks off today, May 20th, followed on Tuesday, May 21st, with the commencement of a three-day National Youth Entrepreneurship Empowerment Summit at the International Conference Centre (ICC) in Abuja.  The Federal Executive Council Valedictory Session will be held at the Council Chambers, State House, Abuja, on Wednesday, May 22nd; a Special Jumat Lecture and prayer will be held on Friday May 24th at the National Mosque; the First Lady’s interaction with women is slated for the Old Chamber at the State House on Saturday May 25th while a special Interdenominational Church Service is slated for Sunday May 26th at the National Christian Centre.  The minister said both May 29th and June 12th would be marked as public holidays this year while assuring maximum security for the celebrations adding that World leaders will only attend the June 12 events.  Our Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan reports that the Minister reiterated that the presidential inauguration ceremony would be low-key as a number of the events slated for the occasion had been moved to June 12 Democracy Day.